                    <!-- Preparation Steps -->
                    <h2 style="font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; margin-top: 40px; color: #141312;">2. Optimization Steps</h2>
                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">01 /</span> <strong>Maillard Base Expansion:</strong> Dice your onions, carrots, and celery uniformly. Sweat them in your pot with oil and sea salt for 8 minutes. Add the tomato paste and spices, frying them directly on the bottom of the pot until the paste turns a deep brick-red to build a robust flavor depth.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">02 /</span> <strong>Hydration & Simmer:</strong> Rinse your dry lentils and drop them into the pot along with your diced potato and vegetable bouillon water. Bring up to a boiling threshold, then drop down to a low simmer for 35 minutes until the lentils are completely tender and have swollen significantly.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">03 /</span> <strong>Starch Crush Thickening:</strong> Use the back of a large wooden spoon to violently mash a fraction of the soft potatoes and lentils against the interior walls of your pot. This releases natural starches directly into the liquid matrix, instantly converting a thin broth into a rich, velvety stew texture.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
